AUDIO: 'then down here is where you would upload the image. Now, for the rest of these settings, I tend to leave them at the default, but let\'s just go over some important values really quickly. for the CFG. This basically controls how'

[20:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'literally you want the AI to follow your text prompt. So, for example, if you want to turn the image into line art, but it\'s not really turning the image into line art, you can try to increase this CFG value to see if it executes'

[20:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'better. Or if you don\'t want it to follow your prompt as literally and you want it to be more creative and add its own thing, then you can also decrease the CFG value. Now, similarly, we also have an image CFG, which basically'

[20:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'controls how literally you want the AI to follow your image or how much it should capture the details of everything in the image. If you want it to really capture everything, then you can try to'

[20:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'increase this value. Or if you want to add more creativity and allow it to change things up a bit, then you can also try to decrease this value to let it be more creative. Again, for me, I just tend to leave both of these at the'

[21:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'default values. And then over here for sampler name and schedule, this is basically the algorithm used to generate the image. Again, I just tend to leave it at ooler simple, but feel free to play around with all these other'

[21:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'algorithms. And then for steps, this is basically like how many iterations you want the AI to go through before outputting your final image. In general, the more steps you have, the higher quality your image would be, but at a certain point, you\'re going to get'

[21:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'diminishing returns. So, if you set this to like 50 steps, that\'s going to be way too much and you\'re just going to be wasting compute. Now, conversely, if you set this to a lower number, let\'s say like 10 steps, then it\'s going to run faster, right? Because it\'s running for'

[21:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fewer steps. But at the same time, you\'re going to sacrifice some quality. So, it turns out that the default value of 20 steps is kind of the sweet spot between speed and quality. So, again, I\'m just going to leave this at 20'

[22:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'steps. And that\'s pretty much it. That\'s basically how you can use this interface. pretty straightforward. Anyways, that sums up my review and installation tutorial of Hydream E1.1. I would say for microediting certain'

